---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Cypress training — grimbergIT"
  description="Cypress workshops by an official Cypress Ambassador. End-to-end tests teams can keep."
>
  <article class="surface">
    <p class="eyebrow">Workshop · 02</p>
    <h1>Cypress</h1>

    <p>
      As one of the four Dutch
      <a href="https://www.cypress.io/ambassadors" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">
        Cypress Ambassadors
      </a>, this is the tool I've spent the most time inside — writing suites, breaking them, and
      helping teams design ones they can keep. If your Cypress suite has become the reason you're
      scared to refactor, this workshop is for you.
    </p>

    <h2>What we cover</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>The fluent API — what it does well, and where it lets intent hide behind cleverness.</li>
      <li>Custom commands worth writing, and the ones that make the suite harder to read later.</li>
      <li>Component vs. end-to-end trade-offs: when to reach for each, and how they compose.</li>
      <li>CI patterns that keep flake out of the pipeline: retries, sharding, and quarantines.</li>
      <li>
        Authentication, network stubbing, and the boring plumbing that most tutorials skip and real
        teams hit on day one.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Format</h2>
    <p>
      One day by default. Splittable into two half-days if the team's calendar prefers it. Also
      available as a multi-week cohort with weekly sessions and homework repos between them.
      In-house or remote — either works.
    </p>

    <h2>What you leave with</h2>
    <p>
      A refactored piece of your own suite, a written recap of the decisions we made, and enough of
      an internal model that the team can keep going without me in the room.
    </p>

    <p>
      <a href="/training/">← Back to training</a> ·
      <a href="/contact">Book a session →</a>
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
